00:44:49.550 --> 00:44:56.710
a couple of years ago which was a pretty good
success. And India's plan now is to send their

00:44:56.710 --> 00:45:02.230
first astronaut into space in 2015, which
is something in terms of individual nations

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:09.230
only three nations have done -- that's China,
U.S., and the Soviet Union. And that astronaut

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:13.720
or those astronauts will go up in a rocket
something like this which is a geosynchronous

00:45:13.720 --> 00:45:17.320
satellite launch vehicle. It'll probably be
a bit bigger than that and so they're working

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:22.270
on that now, working on the technology just
not, not just the rocket technology but also

00:45:22.270 --> 00:45:26.670
making these things habitable which is actually
a huge scientific challenge.

00:45:26.670 --> 00:45:31.609
And I think this demonstrates in terms of
space especially, demonstrate India's raw

00:45:31.609 --> 00:45:37.810
ambition when it comes to science and that
even though people might look at India and

00:45:37.810 --> 00:45:42.349
say, "Why is this poor country investing so
much in science and tech?" It is playing the

00:45:42.349 --> 00:45:46.880
long game, it is thinking about the far, far
future --

